<h2>Overview</h2><p>Removing the fuel tank from your 2004 Jeep Wrangler TJ can be a daunting task, but it’s essential for various upgrades and repairs. In this tutorial, we'll take a close look at the process, step by step, enabling you to tackle this job with confidence.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>In this guide, we will go over the complete removal process of the fuel tank, focusing on:</p><ul><li>Preparation steps to safely remove the tank</li><li>How to disconnect the fuel line connectors</li><li>Tools and tips for a smooth removal</li></ul><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><p>Let’s get started with the necessary steps for removing the fuel tank:</p><ol><li><strong>Preparation:</strong> Before beginning, make sure the vehicle is in a safe position, ideally on a flat surface with the tires removed for better access. Drop the axle if necessary, as this can make the entire process easier.</li><li><strong>Relieve Fuel Pressure:</strong> The very first task is to relieve any pressure in the fuel system. This is done by removing the fuel pump relay, which prevents fuel from reaching the lines while you work.</li><li><strong>Disconnect Fuel Lines:</strong> The fuel lines on a Jeep Wrangler TJ have simple push connectors. Identify these connectors, push the designated area to release them, and detach carefully.</li><li><strong>Remove Other Connectors:</strong> Be sure to check for any additional lines, such as breather tubes and electrical connections that may be attached to the fuel tank.</li><li><strong>Secure the Tank:</strong> Use a jack to hold the tank from below as you start removing the mounting screws. Make sure everything is adequately supported.</li><li><strong>Unscrew Mounts:</strong> Remove the screws or nuts securing the tank to the frame, ensuring that you have taken out all necessary fasteners before lowering the tank.</li><li><strong>Lower the Tank:</strong> With all connections detached and the tank secure, carefully lower it using the jack. Be cautious of the filler neck and other remaining connections.</li></ol><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><ul><li>Ensure you have PB Blaster or a similar penetrating oil handy to loosen any rusted screws or nuts.</li><li>Keeping the fuel tank as empty as possible will reduce weight, but if it’s not feasible, just balance properly.</li><li>Document the disconnection of any wires or hoses for easier reassembly.</li><li>Consider using a clean surface to place the fuel tank for safety and organization.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>Removing the fuel tank from your 2004 Jeep Wrangler TJ is not only necessary for maintenance but also opens up opportunities for various upgrades, including installing a new rear bumper or replacing the fuel pump. With the right tools and preparation, you can efficiently complete this task. Remember to follow the steps carefully, disconnect all necessary components, and always prioritize safety!</p>

